    "summary": "The Nanyue Kingdom (204–111 BC) was a state founded by the former Qin general Zhao Tuo in what is now Guangdong and northern Vietnam, which maintained independence from Han China for nearly a century through skillful diplomacy and strategic geography before being finally conquered by [[event:1127|Emperor Wu of Han]].\n\nZhao Tuo had been sent by Qin to govern the newly conquered southern territories. When the [[event:1123|Fall of the Qin Dynasty]] created chaos in the north, he declared independence, initially submitting to Han suzerainty when convenient but maintaining actual autonomy. The kingdom blended Chinese administrative culture with the traditions of the local Yue (Viet) peoples, creating a distinctive culture visible in the remarkable burial goods of Zhao Mo (second king of Nanyue) discovered in Guangzhou in 1983. Nanyue controlled trade routes to Southeast Asia and the Indian Ocean, and its capital Panyu (modern Guangzhou) became an early maritime trade hub. Han's conquest of Nanyue in 111 BC incorporated the region permanently into the Chinese sphere and brought northern Vietnam under Han administration, establishing a connection between China and Vietnam that would last, with interruptions, until 939 AD.",
